description: Require direct backend or edge fetches for all server-side operations
alwaysApply: true
---

# Direct Backend And Edge Fetches

- For any server-side operation, fetch directly from the authoritative backend or edge endpoint.
- This applies to FastAPI services, scripts, jobs, Next.js server components, server actions, route handlers, middleware, and edge runtime code.
- Do not make server-side calls to frontend proxy routes, browser-oriented BFF endpoints, or same-app API shims when a direct backend or edge target exists.
- Treat `src/app/api/**` proxy handlers as browser-facing adapters unless the task is specifically to implement or maintain that edge surface.
- When server code needs data or mutation capability, use the backend or edge base URL directly through shared server utilities and typed contracts.
- Keep domain separation intact: public storefront traffic stays on the storefront domain, while internal or privileged server operations talk directly to backend or approved edge infrastructure.

## Good

```ts
await fetch(`${backendBaseUrl}/v1/reservations`, { cache: "no-store" });
await fetch(`${edgeBaseUrl}/seo/revalidate`, { method: "POST" });
```

## Reject

```ts
await fetch(`${siteUrl}/api/reservations`);
await fetch(`${siteUrl}/api/internal/revalidate`);
```
